summary:
Reporter Rose Tyler follows a rather irritating lead.
"You've been following me again."
"Well, you've left a trail from London...
body:
Reporter Rose Tyler follows a rather irritating lead.

“You’ve been following me again.”

“Well, you’ve left a trail from London to Oxfordshire and back again. You’re not exactly subtle.”

“I was preventing the apocalypse, Rose! There was hardly time for subtlety.”

“And last night?”

“The cabbie was irritating me.”

“Demons are so predictable. C'mon, Crowley, with me. This cover-up isn’t going to write itself.”

“Can I take my ice lolly?”

“Only if you go back and pay for it.”

I mean, it’s not the kind of thing you don’t notice, your car being on fire. A tongue...
text:
“Excuse me, young man,” he said.
“Yes?”
I mean, it’s not the kind of thing you don’t notice, your car being on fire. A tongue of flame licked across the charred dashboard.
“Funny weather we’re having, isn’t it?” he said, lamely. “Is it?” said Crowley. “I honestly hadn’t noticed.” And he reversed back down the country lane in his burning car.
“That’s probably because your car is on fire,” said R. P. Tyler sharply. He jerked Shutzi’s lead, dragged the little dog to heel.
source: GOOD OMENS Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett

summary:
In which Rose Tyler and Anthony Crowley go on a surprisingly fluffy date.
"Oh my God! You're one of those horrible purists who...
body:
In which Rose Tyler and Anthony Crowley go on a surprisingly fluffy date.

“Oh my God! You’re one of those horrible purists who thinks it’s sacrilege to listen to digital downloads or whatever.” Rose pressed a hand to her mouth, feigning shock but radiating amusement. “You’re a snob!”

“I’m a demon, if you please,” sniffed Crowley, thumbing through the dusty collection of records the shop had to offer, “and therefore have no sense of sacrilege.”

“But still a snob?” she prodded. “C'mon, admit it. You’re a stodgy old man who probably hates modern art and Sriracha and texting. Come to think of it, do you even have a mobile?”

This prompted a long-suffering sigh. “My people invented mobiles, Rose Tyler, and you’d do well to remember that.”

She plucked the album he was perusing out of his hands and arched a brow. “Queen’s Greatest Hits?”

“What? It’s good.”

“Let’s get it and go, then,” she answered, tucking the album under her elbow. “I’m getting hungry. And the museum closes at five.”

“Fine,” he sighed. “But I won’t let you ruin my perfectly good food with copious quantities of cut-rate hellspice. It’s boring.”

Rose’s eyes glittered as she clasped Crowley’s hand in hers. His hand felt cool to the touch, and a bit slippery, like he was sort of trying to slough her off, but not putting much effort in.

“You’re talking about Sriracha, aren’t you? You really do hate it.” She giggled, and the sound gave Crowley a mild but not unpleasant headache. “You old codger.”

“Hush, you,” said the demon fondly. As they left the shop, hand-in-hand, only one of them realized they’d just flagrantly shoplifted.

summary: From Eden by Hozier  Babe, there’s something tragic about you Something so magic about you Don’t you agree? Babe, there’s...
caption:
From Eden by Hozier 

Babe, there’s something tragic about you
Something so magic about you
Don’t you agree?

Babe, there’s something lonesome about you
Something so wholesome about you
Get closer to me

Babe, there’s something wretched about this
Something so precious about this
Oh what a sin

Honey you’re familiar like my mirror years ago
Idealism sits in prison, chivalry fell on it’s sword
Innocence died screaming, honey ask me I should know
I slithered here from Eden just to sit outside your door

summary: "Here's to The Next Time: An Ineffable Zine" is a Good Omens (Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett) fanzine that will cover the...
caption:
“Here’s to The Next Time: An Ineffable Zine” is a Good Omens (Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett) fanzine that will cover the development of the relationship between the angel Aziraphale and the demon Crowley from Eden to the Apocalypse. Six thousand years in the making, the zine will be composed of 21 historical illustrations by 16 different artists.  

Please reblog for interest check.
